 volume, scholars positioned differently with respect to white privilege examine how privilege of all forms manifests itself and how we can, and must, be aware of invisible privilege in our daily lives. Individual chapters focus on language, the workplace, the implications of comparing racism and sexism, race-based housing privilege, the dream of diversity and the cycle of exclusion, the rule of law and invisible systems of privilege, and the power of law to transform society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aPower (Social sciences)zUnited States. 7aLAW / Discrimination.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Margalynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Margalynne.1 aArmstrong, Marêalynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Adrienne D.1 aDavis, Adrienne D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrillo, Trina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrillo, Trina.1 aWildman, Stephanie M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWildman, Stepnanie M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479878949423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479878949.jpg  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK